On Linux, our game has rather bad performance when compared to the XNA Windows or the Monogame MacOS builds, with frequent stuttering and generally lower framerate (to the point of unplayable).

I've profiled the app and I'm pretty sure that the culprit is the GraphicsDevice.ApplyRenderTargets() method, around these lines:

GL.BindFramebuffer(GLFramebuffer, this.glRenderTargetFrameBuffer);  
GL.FramebufferTexture2D(GLFramebuffer, GLColorAttachment0, TextureTarget.Texture2D, renderTarget.glTexture, 0);

// Reverted this change, as per @prollin's suggestion
GL.FramebufferRenderbuffer(GLFramebuffer, GLDepthAttachment, GLRenderbuffer, renderTarget.glDepthBuffer);
GL.FramebufferRenderbuffer(GLFramebuffer, GLStencilAttachment, GLRenderbuffer, renderTarget.glStencilBuffer);

I've tried different things and found out that when using POT rendertargets (such as 1024x1024), it performs way faster than using NPOT.

Not sure what should be done though, but I think I'm going to force POT sized rendertargets on our app for now, even if they end up being larger.

GL.GetUniformLocation causes a rendering pipeline stall in OpenGL, but MonoGame calls it a lot.

The problem seems to be that ConstantBuffer.Apply gives up and calls it any time it notices that the current shader program has changed:

``` csharp
            // NOTE: We assume here the program has 
            // already been set on the device.

            // If the program changed then lookup the
            // uniform again and apply the state.
            if (_program != program)
            {
                var location = GL.GetUniformLocation(program, _name);
                GraphicsExtensions.CheckGLError();
                if (location == -1)
                    return;

                _program = program;
                _location = location;
                _dirty = true;
            }
```

This can end up happening dozens or hundreds of times per frame - in my profiles it accounts for hundreds of thousands of milliseconds of profile time, dwarfing the actual time spent running game logic and actually drawing.

I think this can be fixed by caching uniform locations given a <program, name> tuple. The cache needs to be flushed any time a new program is created, since it's possible a program ID will get reused, but that's the only caveat I can think of. Flushing upon creation of a new program is pretty simple given that everything goes through the cache.
